        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "God’s",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " hand is therefore ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "His",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " hand in the accomplishment of the work, during the performance of which He administers and carries into execution the power, love, and so forth of God. The unity, therefore, is one of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "dynamic",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " fellowship, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". a unity of action for the realization of the divine decree of redemption; according to which, the Father is in the Son, and moves in Him, so that the Father acts in the things which are done by the Son, and yet is greater than the Son (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 14:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), because He has commissioned, consecrated, and sent Him. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Arian",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " idea of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "ethical agreement",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is insufficient; the reasoning would miss its mark unless unity of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "power",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " be understood (on which Chrysostom, Euth. Zigabenus, and many others, also Lücke, justly lay emphasis). The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "orthodox",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " interpretation, which makes it denote ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unity of essence",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (Nonnus: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἓν γένος ἐσμεν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Augustine: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unum",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", delivers us from Charybdis, that is, from Arius, and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sumus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " from Scylla, that is, from Sabellius), specially defended by Hengstenberg, though rejected even by Calvin as a misuse of the passage, goes beyond the argumentation; at the same time, in view of the metaphysical character of the relation of the Son to the Father, clearly taught elsewhere, and especially in John, the Homoousia, as the essential foundation, must be regarded as presupposed in the fellowship here denoted by ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
