  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 29.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - The last statement is sustained by a still loftier assumption. Before translating, it is necessary to notice the three readings of the text. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(1)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " That of the T.R. and the Revisers' Text: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "My Father who gave",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "to me is greater than all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the powers that can possibly be arrayed against them. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "note_emph",
        "text": "(2)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The reading of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "א",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", D, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "With reference to that which my  Father",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "One greater than all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "gave me",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "and no one is able to pluck from the hand of the Father",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Meyer, however, translates this differently; he supposes the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μεῖζον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to refer to the Father \"a something greater, a greater potence.\" Westcott and Hort prefer the reading with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ὅ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "μείζον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and Westcott translates, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "That which my Father has given me is greater than all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and regards it as a reference to the sheep as a collective unity. The internal reasons compel Luthardt, Godet, and Lange to fall back on T.R., and surely the extraordinary strain of the meaning justifies them. Our Lord would sustain with even stronger assurance the safety of his sheep. The Father's gift to himself, the Father's own eternal love and power, the Divine omnipotence of the Lord God himself, is pledged to their security. \"My hand\" becomes \"my Father's hand.\" He seems to say, \"If you question my capacity, you need not question his power. Sacrilegious violence may apparently nail my hands to the cross; the sword may awake against Jehovah's Shepherd. But none can outwit, surprise, crucify, conquer, my Father, none can invalidate his care.\" John 10:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Vincent's Word Studies",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "My Father, which gave them me, is greater than all (ὁ πατήρ μου ὃς δέδωκέ μοι, μείζων πάντων ἐστιν)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "There is considerable confusion here about the reading. Westcott and Hort and Tischendorf read ὁ πατήρ μου (Tischendorf rejects μου) ὃ δέδωκέν μοι πάντων μεῖζόν ἐστιν. That which the Father (or my Father) hath given me is greater than all. Rev. gives this in the margin. For gave, render hath given. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
